{"paragraphs":[{"cues":[{"time":0,"text":"I think all of us have been interested, at one time or another,"},{"time":4000,"text":"in the romantic mysteries of all those societies that collapsed,"},{"time":9000,"text":"such as the classic Maya in the Yucatan, the Easter Islanders,"},{"time":14000,"text":"the Anasazi, Fertile Crescent society, Angor Wat, Great Zimbabwe"},{"time":18000,"text":"and so on. And within the last decade or two,"},{"time":22000,"text":"archaeologists have shown us that there were environmental problems"},{"time":26000,"text":"underlying many of these past collapses."},{"time":29000,"text":"But there were also plenty of places in the world"},{"time":30000,"text":"where societies have been developing for thousands of years"},{"time":34000,"text":"without any sign of a major collapse,"},{"time":36000,"text":"such as Japan, Java, Tonga and Tikopea. So evidently, societies"},{"time":42000,"text":"in some areas are more fragile than in other areas."},{"time":45000,"text":"How can we understand what makes some societies more fragile"},{"time":48000,"text":"than other societies? The problem is obviously relevant"},{"time":54000,"text":"to our situation today, because today as well, there are"},{"time":57000,"text":"some societies that have already collapsed, such as Somalia"},{"time":61000,"text":"and Rwanda and the former Yugoslavia. There are also"},{"time":64000,"text":"societies today that may be close to collapse, such as Nepal, Indonesia and Columbia."}]},{"cues":[{"time":69000,"text":"What about ourselves?"},{"time":72000,"text":"What is there that we can learn from the past that would help us avoid"},{"time":78000,"text":"declining or collapsing in the way that so many past societies have?"},{"time":83000,"text":"Obviously the answer to this question is not going"},{"time":85000,"text":"to be a single factor. If anyone tells you that there is a single-factor"},{"time":89000,"text":"explanation for societal collapses, you know right away"},{"time":92000,"text":"that they're an idiot. This is a complex subject."},{"time":96000,"text":"But how can we make sense out of the complexities of this subject?"},{"time":100000,"text":"In analyzing societal collapses, I've arrived at a"},{"time":103000,"text":"five-point framework -- a checklist of things that I go through"},{"time":107000,"text":"to try and understand collapses. And I'll illustrate that five-point"},{"time":112000,"text":"framework by the extinction of the Greenland Norse society."},{"time":117000,"text":"This is a European society with literate records,"},{"time":120000,"text":"so we know a good deal about the people and their motivation."},{"time":124000,"text":"In AD 984 Vikings went out to Greenland, settled Greenland,"},{"time":128000,"text":"and around 1450 they died out -- the society collapsed,"},{"time":132000,"text":"and every one of them ended up dead."}]},{"cues":[{"time":134000,"text":"Why did they all end up dead? Well, in my five-point framework,"},{"time":138000,"text":"the first item on the framework is to look for human impacts"},{"time":142000,"text":"on the environment: people inadvertently destroying the resource"},{"time":145000,"text":"base on which they depend. And in the case of the Viking Norse,"},{"time":150000,"text":"the Vikings inadvertently caused soil erosion and deforestation,"},{"time":155000,"text":"which was a particular problem for them because"},{"time":158000,"text":"they required forests to make charcoal, to make iron."},{"time":161000,"text":"So they ended up an Iron Age European society, virtually"},{"time":165000,"text":"unable to make their own iron. A second item on my checklist is"},{"time":170000,"text":"climate change. Climate can get warmer or colder or dryer or wetter."},{"time":176000,"text":"In the case of the Vikings -- in Greenland, the climate got colder"},{"time":180000,"text":"in the late 1300s, and especially in the 1400s. But a cold climate"},{"time":184000,"text":"isn't necessarily fatal, because the Inuit -- the Eskimos inhabiting"},{"time":189000,"text":"Greenland at the same time -- did better, rather than worse,"},{"time":191000,"text":"with cold climates. So why didn't the Greenland Norse as well?"}]},{"cues":[{"time":195000,"text":"The third thing on my checklist is relations with neighboring"},{"time":199000,"text":"friendly societies that may prop up a society. And if that"},{"time":203000,"text":"friendly support is pulled away, that may make a society"},{"time":206000,"text":"more likely to collapse. In the case of the Greenland Norse,"},{"time":210000,"text":"they had trade with the mother country -- Norway --"},{"time":212000,"text":"and that trade dwindled: partly because Norway got weaker,"},{"time":216000,"text":"partly because of sea ice between Greenland and Norway."}]},{"cues":[{"time":221000,"text":"The fourth item on my checklist is relations with hostile societies."},{"time":227000,"text":"In the case of Norse Greenland, the hostiles were the Inuit --"},{"time":230000,"text":"the Eskimos sharing Greenland -- with whom the Norse"},{"time":234000,"text":"got off to bad relationships. And we know that the Inuit"},{"time":238000,"text":"killed the Norse and, probably of greater importance,"},{"time":241000,"text":"may have blocked access to the outer fjords, on which"},{"time":245000,"text":"the Norse depended for seals at a critical time of the year."}]},{"cues":[{"time":249000,"text":"And then finally, the fifth item on my checklist is the political,"},{"time":253000,"text":"economic, social and cultural factors in the society that make it"},{"time":257000,"text":"more or less likely that the society will perceive and solve its"},{"time":261000,"text":"environmental problems. In the case of the Greenland Norse,"},{"time":266000,"text":"cultural factors that made it difficult for them"},{"time":268000,"text":"to solve their problems were: their commitments to a"},{"time":271000,"text":"Christian society investing heavily in cathedrals; their being"},{"time":275000,"text":"a competitive-ranked chiefly society; and their scorn for the Inuit,"},{"time":281000,"text":"from whom they refused to learn. So that's how the five-part"},{"time":284000,"text":"framework is relevant to the collapse and eventual extinction of the Greenland Norse."}]},{"cues":[{"time":289000,"text":"What about a society today?"},{"time":292000,"text":"For the past five years, I've been taking my wife and kids to"},{"time":296000,"text":"Southwestern Montana, where I worked as a teenager"},{"time":299000,"text":"on the hay harvest. And Montana, at first sight, seems"},{"time":303000,"text":"like the most pristine environment in the United States."},{"time":306000,"text":"But scratch the surface, and Montana suffers from serious problems."},{"time":311000,"text":"Going through the same checklist: human environmental impacts?"},{"time":315000,"text":"Yes, acute in Montana. Toxic problems from mine waste"},{"time":320000,"text":"have caused damage of billions of dollars."},{"time":323000,"text":"Problems from weeds, weed control, cost Montana nearly"},{"time":326000,"text":"200 million dollars a year. Montana has lost agricultural areas"},{"time":330000,"text":"from salinization, problems of forest management,"},{"time":334000,"text":"problems of forest fires. Second item on my checklist:"},{"time":338000,"text":"climate change. Yes -- the climate in Montana is getting warmer"},{"time":341000,"text":"and drier, but Montana agriculture depends especially on irrigation"},{"time":345000,"text":"from the snow pack, and as the snow is melting -- for example,"},{"time":349000,"text":"as the glaciers in Glacier National Park are disappearing --"},{"time":352000,"text":"that's bad news for Montana irrigation agriculture."}]},{"cues":[{"time":356000,"text":"Third thing on my checklist: relations with friendlies"},{"time":358000,"text":"that can sustain the society. In Montana today, more than half of"},{"time":362000,"text":"the income of Montana is not earned within Montana,"},{"time":366000,"text":"but is derived from out of state: transfer payments from"},{"time":369000,"text":"social security, investments and so on --"},{"time":372000,"text":"which makes Montana vulnerable to the rest of the United States."}]},{"cues":[{"time":376000,"text":"Fourth: relations with hostiles. Montanans have the same problems"},{"time":380000,"text":"as do all Americans, in being sensitive to problems"},{"time":384000,"text":"created by hostiles overseas affecting our oil supplies,"},{"time":388000,"text":"and terrorist attacks. And finally, last item on my checklist:"},{"time":394000,"text":"question of how political, economic, social, cultural attitudes"},{"time":397000,"text":"play into this. Montanans have long-held values, which today"},{"time":402000,"text":"seem to be getting in the way of their solving their own problems."},{"time":405000,"text":"Long-held devotion to logging and to mines and to agriculture,"},{"time":409000,"text":"and to no government regulation; values that worked well"},{"time":413000,"text":"in the past, but they don't seem to be working well today."}]},{"cues":[{"time":417000,"text":"So, I'm looking at these issues of collapses"},{"time":419000,"text":"for a lot of past societies and for many present societies."},{"time":424000,"text":"Are there any general conclusions that arise?"},{"time":426000,"text":"In a way, just like Tolstoy's statement about every unhappy marriage"},{"time":431000,"text":"being different, every collapsed or endangered society is different --"},{"time":434000,"text":"they all have different details. But nevertheless, there are certain"},{"time":438000,"text":"common threads that emerge from these comparisons"},{"time":441000,"text":"of past societies that did or did not collapse"},{"time":444000,"text":"and threatened societies today. One interesting common thread"},{"time":451000,"text":"has to do with, in many cases, the rapidity of collapse"},{"time":455000,"text":"after a society reaches its peak. There are many societies"},{"time":459000,"text":"that don't wind down gradually, but they build up -- get richer"},{"time":462000,"text":"and more powerful -- and then within a short time, within a few decades"},{"time":466000,"text":"after their peak, they collapse. For example,"},{"time":468000,"text":"the classic lowland Maya of the Yucatan began to collapse in the"},{"time":474000,"text":"early 800s -- literally a few decades after the Maya were building"},{"time":477000,"text":"their biggest monuments, and Maya population was greatest."}]},{"cues":[{"time":482000,"text":"Or again, the collapse of the Soviet Union took place"},{"time":485000,"text":"within a couple of decades, maybe within a decade, of the time"},{"time":489000,"text":"when the Soviet Union was at its greatest power."},{"time":492000,"text":"An analogue would be the growth of bacteria in a petri dish."},{"time":497000,"text":"These rapid collapses are especially likely where there's"},{"time":500000,"text":"a mismatch between available resources and resource consumption,"},{"time":505000,"text":"or a mismatch between economic outlays and economic potential."},{"time":509000,"text":"In a petri dish, bacteria grow. Say they double every generation,"},{"time":514000,"text":"and five generations before the end the petri dish is 15/16ths empty,"},{"time":519000,"text":"and then the next generation's 3/4ths empty, and the next generation"},{"time":523000,"text":"half empty. Within one generation after the petri dish still"},{"time":527000,"text":"being half empty, it is full. There's no more food and the bacteria have collapsed."},{"time":532000,"text":"So, this is a frequent theme:"},{"time":534000,"text":"societies collapse very soon after reaching their peak in power."}]},{"cues":[{"time":539000,"text":"What it means to put it mathematically is that, if you're concerned"},{"time":541000,"text":"about a society today, you should be looking not at the value"},{"time":546000,"text":"of the mathematical function -- the wealth itself -- but you should"},{"time":549000,"text":"be looking at the first derivative and the second derivatives"},{"time":552000,"text":"of the function. That's one general theme. A second general theme"},{"time":557000,"text":"is that there are many, often subtle environmental factors that make"},{"time":562000,"text":"some societies more fragile than others. Many of those factors"},{"time":566000,"text":"are not well understood. For example, why is it that in the Pacific,"},{"time":570000,"text":"of those hundreds of Pacific islands, why did Easter Island end up as"},{"time":574000,"text":"the most devastating case of complete deforestation?"},{"time":578000,"text":"It turns out that there were about nine different environmental"},{"time":581000,"text":"factors -- some, rather subtle ones -- that were working against"},{"time":585000,"text":"the Easter Islanders, and they involve fallout of volcanic tephra,"},{"time":590000,"text":"latitude, rainfall. Perhaps the most subtle of them"},{"time":593000,"text":"is that it turns out that a major input of nutrients"},{"time":596000,"text":"which protects island environments in the Pacific is from"},{"time":600000,"text":"the fallout of continental dust from central Asia."},{"time":603000,"text":"Easter, of all Pacific islands, has the least input of dust"},{"time":607000,"text":"from Asia restoring the fertility of its soils. But that's"},{"time":611000,"text":"a factor that we didn't even appreciate until 1999."}]},{"cues":[{"time":616000,"text":"So, some societies, for subtle environmental reasons,"},{"time":618000,"text":"are more fragile than others. And then finally,"},{"time":621000,"text":"another generalization. I'm now teaching a course"},{"time":624000,"text":"at UCLA, to UCLA undergraduates, on these collapses"},{"time":627000,"text":"of societies. What really bugs my UCLA undergraduate students is,"},{"time":631000,"text":"how on earth did these societies not see what they were doing?"},{"time":634000,"text":"How could the Easter Islanders have deforested their environment?"},{"time":637000,"text":"What did they say when they were cutting down the last palm tree?"},{"time":641000,"text":"Didn't they see what they were doing? How could societies"},{"time":644000,"text":"not perceive their impacts on the environments and stop in time?"},{"time":649000,"text":"And I would expect that, if our human civilization carries on,"},{"time":656000,"text":"then maybe in the next century people will be asking,"},{"time":659000,"text":"why on earth did these people today in the year 2003 not see"},{"time":663000,"text":"the obvious things that they were doing and take corrective action?"},{"time":667000,"text":"It seems incredible in the past. In the future, it'll seem"},{"time":670000,"text":"incredible what we are doing today. And so I've been"},{"time":673000,"text":"trying to develop a hierarchical set of considerations"},{"time":678000,"text":"about why societies fail to solve their problems --"},{"time":682000,"text":"why they fail to perceive the problems or, if they perceive them,"},{"time":684000,"text":"why they fail to tackle them. Or, if they tackle them,"},{"time":687000,"text":"why do they fail to succeed in solving them?"}]},{"cues":[{"time":690000,"text":"I'll just mention two generalizations in this area."},{"time":694000,"text":"One blueprint for trouble, making collapse likely,"},{"time":697000,"text":"is where there is a conflict of interest between the short-term"},{"time":700000,"text":"interest of the decision-making elites and the long-term"},{"time":704000,"text":"interest of the society as a whole, especially if the elites"},{"time":708000,"text":"are able to insulate themselves from the consequences"},{"time":710000,"text":"of their actions. Where what's good in the short run for the elite"},{"time":714000,"text":"is bad for the society as a whole, there's a real risk of the elite"},{"time":718000,"text":"doing things that would bring the society down in the long run."},{"time":721000,"text":"For example, among the Greenland Norse --"},{"time":723000,"text":"a competitive rank society -- what the chiefs really wanted"},{"time":726000,"text":"is more followers and more sheep and more resources"},{"time":729000,"text":"to outcompete the neighboring chiefs. And that led the chiefs"},{"time":732000,"text":"to do what's called flogging the land: overstocking the land,"},{"time":736000,"text":"forcing tenant farmers into dependency. And that made"},{"time":740000,"text":"the chiefs powerful in the short run,"},{"time":744000,"text":"but led to the society's collapse in the long run."}]},{"cues":[{"time":748000,"text":"Those same issues of conflicts of interest are acute"},{"time":751000,"text":"in the United States today. Especially because"},{"time":754000,"text":"the decision makers in the United States are frequently"},{"time":758000,"text":"able to insulate themselves from consequences"},{"time":761000,"text":"by living in gated compounds, by drinking bottled water"},{"time":764000,"text":"and so on. And within the last couple of years,"},{"time":767000,"text":"it's been obvious that the elite in the business world"},{"time":771000,"text":"correctly perceive that they can advance"},{"time":773000,"text":"their short-term interest by doing things that are"},{"time":776000,"text":"good for them but bad for society as a whole,"},{"time":778000,"text":"such as draining a few billion dollars out of Enron"},{"time":781000,"text":"and other businesses. They are quite correct"},{"time":785000,"text":"that these things are good for them in the short term,"},{"time":788000,"text":"although bad for society in the long term."},{"time":791000,"text":"So, that's one general conclusion about why societies"},{"time":794000,"text":"make bad decisions: conflicts of interest."}]},{"cues":[{"time":798000,"text":"And the other generalization that I want to mention"},{"time":802000,"text":"is that it's particularly hard for a society to make"},{"time":804000,"text":"quote-unquote good decisions when there is a conflict involving"},{"time":810000,"text":"strongly held values that are good in many circumstances"},{"time":815000,"text":"but are poor in other circumstances. For example,"},{"time":818000,"text":"the Greenland Norse, in this difficult environment,"},{"time":821000,"text":"were held together for four-and-a-half centuries"},{"time":824000,"text":"by their shared commitment to religion,"},{"time":827000,"text":"and by their strong social cohesion. But those two things --"},{"time":831000,"text":"commitment to religion and strong social cohesion --"},{"time":834000,"text":"also made it difficult for them to change at the end"},{"time":837000,"text":"and to learn from the Inuit. Or today -- Australia."},{"time":840000,"text":"One of the things that enabled Australia to survive"},{"time":843000,"text":"in this remote outpost of European civilization"},{"time":846000,"text":"for 250 years has been their British identity."},{"time":850000,"text":"But today, their commitment to a British identity"},{"time":854000,"text":"is serving Australians poorly in their need to adapt"},{"time":857000,"text":"to their situation in Asia. So it's particularly difficult"},{"time":861000,"text":"to change course when the things that get you in trouble"},{"time":865000,"text":"are the things that are also the source of your strength."}]},{"cues":[{"time":869000,"text":"What's going to be the outcome today?"},{"time":871000,"text":"Well, all of us know the dozen sorts of ticking time bombs"},{"time":877000,"text":"going on in the modern world, time bombs that have fuses"},{"time":883000,"text":"of a few decades to -- all of them, not more than 50 years,"},{"time":887000,"text":"and any one of which can do us in; the time bombs of water,"},{"time":892000,"text":"of soil, of climate change, invasive species,"},{"time":896000,"text":"the photosynthetic ceiling, population problems, toxics, etc., etc. --"},{"time":901000,"text":"listing about 12 of them. And while these time bombs --"},{"time":905000,"text":"none of them has a fuse beyond 50 years, and most of them"},{"time":907000,"text":"have fuses of a few decades -- some of them, in some places,"},{"time":910000,"text":"have much shorter fuses. At the rate at which we're going now,"},{"time":914000,"text":"the Philippines will lose all its accessible loggable forest"},{"time":918000,"text":"within five years. And the Solomon Islands are only"},{"time":921000,"text":"one year away from losing their loggable forest,"},{"time":924000,"text":"which is their major export. And that's going to be spectacular"},{"time":926000,"text":"for the economy of the Solomons. People often ask me,"},{"time":930000,"text":"Jared, what's the most important thing that we need to do"},{"time":933000,"text":"about the world's environmental problems?"},{"time":935000,"text":"And my answer is, the most important thing we need to do"},{"time":937000,"text":"is to forget about there being any single thing that is"},{"time":940000,"text":"the most important thing we need to do."},{"time":942000,"text":"Instead, there are a dozen things, any one of which could do us in."},{"time":945000,"text":"And we've got to get them all right, because if we solve 11,"},{"time":948000,"text":"we fail to solve the 12th -- we're in trouble. For example,"},{"time":951000,"text":"if we solve our problems of water and soil and population,"},{"time":954000,"text":"but don't solve our problems of toxics, then we are in trouble."}]},{"cues":[{"time":960000,"text":"The fact is that our present course is a non-sustainable course,"},{"time":965000,"text":"which means, by definition, that it cannot be maintained."},{"time":969000,"text":"And the outcome is going to get resolved within a few decades."},{"time":976000,"text":"That means that those of us in this room who are less than"},{"time":979000,"text":"50 or 60 years old will see how these paradoxes are resolved,"},{"time":983000,"text":"and those of us who are over the age of 60 may not see"},{"time":986000,"text":"the resolution, but our children and grandchildren certainly will."},{"time":990000,"text":"The resolution is going to achieve either of two forms:"},{"time":993000,"text":"either we will resolve these non-sustainable time-fuses"},{"time":998000,"text":"in pleasant ways of our own choice by taking remedial action,"},{"time":1003000,"text":"or else these conflicts are going to get settled"},{"time":1006000,"text":"in unpleasant ways not of our choice -- namely, by war,"},{"time":1010000,"text":"disease or starvation. But what's for sure is that our"},{"time":1014000,"text":"non-sustainable course will get resolved in one way or another"},{"time":1016000,"text":"in a few decades. In other words, since the theme of this session"},{"time":1020000,"text":"is choices, we have a choice. Does that mean that we should"},{"time":1025000,"text":"get pessimistic and overwhelmed? I draw the reverse conclusion."}]},{"cues":[{"time":1030000,"text":"The big problems facing the world today are not at all"},{"time":1033000,"text":"things beyond our control. Our biggest threat is not an asteroid"},{"time":1037000,"text":"about to crash into us, something we can do nothing about."},{"time":1041000,"text":"Instead, all the major threats facing us today are problems"},{"time":1044000,"text":"entirely of our own making. And since we made the problems,"},{"time":1048000,"text":"we can also solve the problems. That then means that it's"},{"time":1052000,"text":"entirely in our power to deal with these problems."},{"time":1056000,"text":"In particular, what can all of us do? For those of you"},{"time":1059000,"text":"who are interested in these choices, there are lots of things"},{"time":1062000,"text":"you can do. There's a lot that we don't understand,"},{"time":1066000,"text":"and that we need to understand. And there's a lot that"},{"time":1069000,"text":"we already do understand, but aren't doing, and that"},{"time":1073000,"text":"we need to be doing. Thank you."},{"time":1075000,"text":"(Applause)"}]}]}